---
import Text from '@/components/Text/Text.astro';
import List from '@/components/List/List.astro';
import ListItem from '@/components/List/ListItem.astro';
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="Why Open Source? | LibreCourseUY"
	description="Learn why open source matters and how LibreCourseUY is changing the open source landscape in Uruguay."
>
	<main class="flex min-h-screen flex-col items-start justify-center">
		<section class="flex flex-col justify-start items-start w-full min-h-dvh mt-12 md:pt-12">
			<div class="space-y-12 w-full max-w-4xl">
				<div class="space-y-4">
					<Text variant="h1">Why Open Source?</Text>
					<Text variant="p">
						Open source is more than sharing code, it's a global collaboration model that
						accelerates innovation and democratizes access to technology.
					</Text>
				</div>

				<hr class="border-neutral-700" />

				<div class="space-y-4">
					<Text variant="h2">What is Open Source?</Text>
					<Text variant="p">
						<strong>Open source</strong> is a software development model in which the source code is
						published openly so that anyone can study, modify, and redistribute it. This means that
						instead of keeping the code private within a company, developers make it publicly available
						under a license that allows others to use, modify, and share the code.
					</Text>
					<Text variant="p">
						The open source movement has grown tremendously over the past few decades. What started as a
						niche movement among academics and hobbyists has become the dominant model for building
						software. Today, companies like Google, Microsoft, Meta, and Amazon not only use open source
						software extensively but also release much of their own code as open source.
					</Text>
					<Text variant="p">
						More than a simple way to share code, open source has become a global collaboration model
						that accelerates innovation and democratizes access to technology. It allows developers from
						anywhere in the world to work together on projects, share knowledge, and build upon each
						other's work.
					</Text>
				</div>

				<hr class="border-neutral-700" />

				<div class="space-y-4">
					<Text variant="h2">A Brief History</Text>
					<Text variant="p">
						The concept of sharing source code has existed since the early days of computing. In the
						1950s and 1960s, software was typically shared freely along with hardware, and developers
						routinely exchanged code and improvements.
					</Text>
					<Text variant="p">
						However, in the 1970s and 1980s, the software industry began to change. Companies started
						treating software as a proprietary product, charging for licenses and keeping source code
						secret. This shift led to the creation of organizations like the Free Software Foundation in
						1985, which advocated for software freedom.
					</Text>
					<Text variant="p">
						The term "open source" was coined in 1998 when Netscape released the source code of its
						Navigator browser, and a group of developers met to discuss how to promote this model more
						effectively. Since then, open source has grown to become the foundation of modern software
						development.
					</Text>
				</div>

				<hr class="border-neutral-700" />

				<div class="space-y-4">
					<Text variant="h2">Benefits for Developers</Text>

					<div class="space-y-2">
						<Text variant="h3">Continuous Improvement Through Collective Code Review</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							Publishing code openly allows other developers to review work, identify bugs, propose
							improvements, and contribute new features. This creates a cycle of continuous improvement
							that would be very difficult to achieve working in isolation. When hundreds or thousands
							of developers can examine and contribute to a project, bugs are found faster, code quality
							improves, and new features are added more quickly.
						</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							In contrast to proprietary development, where only a small team sees the code, open
							source projects benefit from diverse perspectives and expertise from around the world.
						</Text>
					</div>

					<div class="space-y-2">
						<Text variant="h3">Better Engineering Practices</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							Maintaining an open project forces developers to adopt good engineering practices. When
							your code is publicly visible, you naturally write clearer code, document properly, and
							design maintainable architectures. You also learn to handle contributions from others,
							manage discussions, and coordinate work among multiple contributors.
						</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							Over time, this process improves both the quality of the project and the skills of the
							developer. Many experienced engineers credit their growth to working on open source
							projects.
						</Text>
					</div>

					<div class="space-y-2">
						<Text variant="h3">Professional Visibility and Career Opportunities</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							A successful open source project serves as a public portfolio that demonstrates real
							capabilities. Unlike certifications or degrees, open source contributions show actual code
							you've written, problems you've solved, and how you collaborate with others.
						</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							Many tech companies analyze code repositories to evaluate how candidates think and work.
							Companies like Google, Meta, and Microsoft have been known to actively recruit developers
							who have contributed to major open source projects. Participating actively in open source
							can be a gateway to job opportunities, freelance work, or academic collaborations.
						</Text>
					</div>

					<div class="space-y-2">
						<Text variant="h3">Networking and Community Building</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							Open source provides an opportunity to connect with developers from around the world who
							share similar interests. These connections can lead to friendships, mentorships, job
							opportunities, and collaborations on new projects.
						</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							Many open source communities are welcoming environments where beginners can learn from
							experienced developers and gradually become contributors themselves. Organizations like
							LibreCourseUY are examples of communities that foster this kind of growth.
						</Text>
					</div>

					<div class="space-y-2">
						<Text variant="h3">Learning from Real-World Code</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							One of the greatest benefits of open source is the ability to study how experienced
							developers solve problems. By reading source code of popular projects, you can learn
							design patterns, best practices, and new technologies.
						</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							This kind of learning is invaluable because it exposes you to production-quality code
							that has been tested and refined by many contributors. It's much more effective than
							learning from tutorials or courses that often use simplified examples.
						</Text>
					</div>
				</div>

				<hr class="border-neutral-700" />

				<div class="space-y-4">
					<Text variant="h2">Benefits for Industry</Text>

					<div class="space-y-2">
						<Text variant="h3">Cost Reduction and Economic Efficiency</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							Many fundamental tools can be used without paying expensive licenses. Technologies like
							Linux, PostgreSQL, Kubernetes, Apache HTTP Server, and MySQL are examples of open source
							software that today form part of the infrastructure of companies worldwide.
						</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							By using these tools, organizations can invest more resources in developing proprietary
							products and unique value propositions instead of spending large sums on software
							licenses. This is particularly important for startups and small companies with limited
							budgets.
						</Text>
					</div>

					<div class="space-y-2">
						<Text variant="h3">Transparency and Security</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							When code is publicly available, it can be audited by thousands of developers and
							security experts around the world. This collective review process allows vulnerabilities
							to be detected faster and fixed more quickly than in proprietary software, where only the
							internal team has access to the code.
						</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							High-profile security incidents in proprietary software have demonstrated that closed
							code is not necessarily more secure. In fact, many open source projects have robust
							security track records precisely because of the extensive review they receive.
						</Text>
					</div>

					<div class="space-y-2">
						<Text variant="h3">Technological Independence</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							When a company depends on proprietary software, it becomes tied to the vendor that
							develops it. If the vendor changes the terms of use, increases prices significantly, or
							abandons the project, the company has few alternatives and may face costly migrations.
						</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							With open source software, organizations have the freedom to modify the code, adapt it to
							their specific needs, or even maintain their own version of the project if necessary.
							This reduces the risk of vendor lock-in and gives companies greater control over the
							tools they use.
						</Text>
					</div>

					<div class="space-y-2">
						<Text variant="h3">Large-Scale Innovation</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							By allowing developers and companies from around the world to collaborate on the same
							project, an ecosystem is created in which technological progress occurs much faster. Even
							competing companies can collaborate on shared infrastructure while competing in their
							final products.
						</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							Organizations like the Linux Foundation coordinate entire communities dedicated to
							developing critical digital infrastructure. Projects like Kubernetes, TensorFlow, and VS
							Code have transformed entire industries through collaborative development.
						</Text>
					</div>

					<div class="space-y-2">
						<Text variant="h3">Faster Development and Time-to-Market</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							Companies can leverage existing open source components to build products faster instead
							of reinventing the wheel. This significantly reduces development time and allows
							companies to focus their resources on the unique aspects of their products.
						</Text>
						<Text variant="p">
							The ability to build on top of proven, community-tested components also reduces risk and
							improves overall software quality.
						</Text>
					</div>
				</div>

				<hr class="border-neutral-700" />

				<div class="space-y-4">
					<Text variant="h2">Open Source in Uruguay</Text>
					<Text variant="p">
						Despite the global growth of open source, Uruguay presents a concerning reality. The vast
						majority of code produced by Uruguayan developers is private, meaning the local open source
						community remains small and fragmented. While some government initiatives have promoted open
						source software, there is a significant gap between using open source tools and contributing
						back to the community.
					</Text>
					<Text variant="p">
						This situation represents both a challenge and an opportunity. On one hand, Uruguay risks
						falling behind in the global open source ecosystem, missing out on the benefits of
						collaboration, visibility, and talent development that come with contributing to open source
						projects. On the other hand, there is enormous potential to grow a vibrant local community
						that can make meaningful contributions.
					</Text>
				</div>

				<hr class="border-neutral-700" />

				<div class="space-y-4">
					<Text variant="h2">LibreCourseUY: Changing the Reality</Text>
					<Text variant="p">
						<strong>LibreCourseUY</strong> was created with a clear purpose: to change the current state
						of open source in Uruguay. We believe that by fostering a culture of contribution among
						interested developers, we can help reverse this trend and build a stronger, more collaborative
						tech community.
					</Text>
					<Text variant="p">Our mission is to:</Text>
					<List className="list-disc pl-6">
						<ListItem>
							<Text variant="p">
								<strong>Democratize access to technology education</strong> by providing free,
								high-quality learning resources
							</Text>
						</ListItem>
						<ListItem>
							<Text variant="p">
								<strong>Promote open source culture</strong> among individuals and the wider community
							</Text>
						</ListItem>
						<ListItem>
							<Text variant="p">
								<strong>Provide hands-on experience</strong> with real projects that individuals can
								contribute to
							</Text>
						</ListItem>
						<ListItem>
							<Text variant="p">
								<strong>Build a supportive community</strong> where individuals can learn from each
								other
							</Text>
						</ListItem>
						<ListItem>
							<Text variant="p">
								<strong>Bridge the gap between academia and industry</strong> by teaching practical
								skills that are in high demand
							</Text>
						</ListItem>
						<ListItem>
							<Text variant="p">
								<strong>Increase Uruguay's visibility</strong> in the global open source ecosystem
							</Text>
						</ListItem>
					</List>
					<Text variant="p">
						We believe that everyone should have access to quality technological education, regardless of
						their background or economic situation. By embracing open source, we not only give individuals
						access to powerful tools but also teach them how to contribute to and benefit from the global
						software development community.
					</Text>
				</div>
			</div>
		</section>
		<footer class="min-h-64 flex flex-row gap-x-12 justify-end items-end pb-12">
			<span class="text-emphasis/60">Libre<span>Course</span>UY</span>
			<span class="footer-copy">© 2026 | Open Source Education</span>
		</footer>
	</main>
</Layout>
